<section class="bmi-section" id="understanding">
  <div class="section-label">Understanding Obesity</div>
  <h2>What is obesity and <em>why does it matter?</em></h2>
  <p class="section-intro">Obesity is a complex, chronic medical condition — not a lifestyle choice. It affects nearly every organ system and dramatically increases the risk of serious disease.</p>

  <div class="bmi-grid">
    <div>
      <p style="color: var(--warm-gray); font-weight: 300; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">Body Mass Index (BMI) is one of the primary screening tools used to classify weight status. It is calculated as weight (kg) divided by height squared (m²). While it has limitations, it remains a useful starting point for clinical assessment.</p>
      <table class="bmi-table">
        <thead>
          <tr><th>BMI Range</th><th>Classification</th><th>Health Risk</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Below 18.5</td><td><span class="tag tag-blue">Underweight</span></td><td>Increased</td></tr>
          <tr><td>18.5 – 24.9</td><td><span class="tag tag-green">Normal weight</span></td><td>Low</td></tr>
          <tr><td>25.0 – 29.9</td><td><span class="tag tag-amber">Overweight</span></td><td>Moderate</td></tr>
          <tr><td>30.0 – 34.9</td><td><span class="tag tag-red">Obese Class I</span></td><td>High</td></tr>
          <tr><td>35.0 – 39.9</td><td><span class="tag tag-red">Obese Class II</span></td><td>Very High</td></tr>
          <tr><td>40.0 and above</td><td><span class="tag tag-darkred">Obese Class III</span></td><td>Extremely High</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p style="font-size: 0.8rem; color: var(--warm-gray); margin-top: 1rem; font-style: italic;">Note: BMI thresholds for Asian populations are typically lower. Waist circumference and other metabolic markers are also important.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="bmi-image">
      <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1535914254981-b5012eebbd15?w=700&q=80" alt="Doctor discussing health with patient">
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

