<!-- MEDICAL TREATMENT -->
<section class="medical-section" id="medical">
  <div class="section-label">Medical Treatment</div>
  <h2>When lifestyle alone <em>needs support</em></h2>
  <p class="section-intro">For many patients, medical and pharmacological interventions significantly improve outcomes when combined with lifestyle modification.</p>
  <div class="medical-grid">
    <div class="medical-image">
      <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1505751172876-fa1923c5c528?w=700&q=80" alt="Medical consultation with doctor">
    </div>
    <div>
      <div class="treatment-list">
        <div class="treatment-item highlight">
          <h4>Comprehensive Medical Assessment</h4>
          <p>Full evaluation including BMI, waist circumference, blood pressure, lipid profile, HbA1c, thyroid function, and cardiovascular risk scoring to guide personalised treatment.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="treatment-item">
          <h4>Pharmacotherapy</h4>
          <p>Approved weight-loss medications (e.g. Orlistat, GLP-1 receptor agonists) may be appropriate for BMI ≥30 or ≥27 with comorbidities, when diet and exercise are insufficient.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="treatment-item">
          <h4>Comorbidity Management</h4>
          <p>Simultaneous management of related conditions — type 2 diabetes, hypertension, dyslipidaemia, PCOS, and sleep apnoea — is integral to successful weight management.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="treatment-item">
          <h4>Bariatric Surgery Referral</h4>
          <p>For eligible patients with BMI ≥40, or ≥35 with severe comorbidities, surgical options (sleeve gastrectomy, gastric bypass) may be considered via specialist referral.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="treatment-item">
          <h4>Regular Monitoring & Follow-up</h4>
          <p>Structured follow-up visits every 4–8 weeks to monitor progress, adjust treatment, and provide ongoing support — accountability is key to long-term success.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- MENTAL / BEHAVIOURAL -->
<section class="mental-section" id="mental">
  <div class="section-label">Behavioural Support</div>
  <h2>The <em>mind-body</em> connection in weight management</h2>
  <p class="section-intro">Psychological and behavioural factors are often the missing piece in weight management. Addressing them is essential for sustainable results.</p>
  <div class="mental-cards">
    <div class="mental-card">
      <div class="mental-card-num">01</div>
      <h4>Cognitive Behavioural Techniques</h4>
      <p>Identifying and changing unhelpful thought patterns around food, body image, and self-worth. Reframing setbacks as learning opportunities rather than failures.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="mental-card">
      <div class="mental-card-num">02</div>
      <h4>Emotional Eating Awareness</h4>
      <p>Recognising triggers that drive eating in the absence of hunger — stress, boredom, loneliness — and developing alternative coping strategies that don't involve food.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="mental-card">
      <div class="mental-card-num">03</div>
      <h4>Sleep & Stress Management</h4>
      <p>Poor sleep raises ghrelin and reduces leptin, promoting hunger and cravings. Chronic stress elevates cortisol, driving abdominal fat deposition. Both must be addressed.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="mental-card">
      <div class="mental-card-num">04</div>
      <h4>Goal Setting & Self-Monitoring</h4>
      <p>SMART goal-setting, food diaries, step counting, and regular weigh-ins with clinical support have consistently been shown to improve weight loss outcomes.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="mental-card">
      <div class="mental-card-num">05</div>
      <h4>Social Support Networks</h4>
      <p>Family involvement, peer support groups, and community-based programmes substantially improve adherence to lifestyle change and long-term weight maintenance.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="mental-card">
      <div class="mental-card-num">06</div>
      <h4>Relapse Prevention</h4>
      <p>Weight regain is common and normal. Having a structured plan for high-risk periods, holidays, and stress events significantly reduces the severity of regain.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

